00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.517
This lecture is going to be
very dependent upon the

00:00:04.517 --> 00:00:08.119
PowerPoint
slides, because if I take the

00:00:08.119 --> 00:00:11.384
time to draw the cycles on the
board,

00:00:11.384 --> 00:00:13.141
we'd be here forever.

00:00:13.141 --> 00:00:17.076
So I would say sit back and
relax because you

00:00:17.076 --> 00:00:18.455
have the slides.

00:00:18.455 --> 00:00:20.094
They're on the Web.

00:00:20.094 --> 00:00:24.635
And try to focus on what the
take-home message is.

00:00:24.635 --> 00:00:28.460
OK, but before we go on to
biogeochemical

00:00:28.460 --> 00:00:33.715
cycles, I want to just briefly
review some of the things that

00:00:33.715 --> 00:00:36.659
we
learned in the second lecture.

00:00:36.659 --> 00:00:39.500
I got feedback from many of
you,

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:43.617
actually, on the things that
were difficult to understand

00:00:43.617 --> 00:00:46.006
from that
lecture, and those are

00:00:46.006 --> 00:00:48.746
important for understanding
these cycles.

00:00:48.746 --> 00:00:51.960
And the
one thing that some people were

00:00:51.960 --> 00:00:55.333
confused by was this anaerobic
respiration.

00:00:55.333 --> 00:00:59.500
Remember, I drew this on the
board, and it showed a lot of

00:00:59.500 --> 00:01:01.204
reduction reactions.

00:01:01.204 --> 00:01:04.272
And I think that was confusing
for

00:01:04.272 --> 00:01:07.103
some people,
so let's just go over that very

00:01:07.103 --> 00:01:07.630
quickly.

00:01:07.630 --> 00:01:10.551
You've learned
in Graham's lectures,

00:01:10.551 --> 00:01:13.361
and in my lectures,
that aerobic

00:01:13.361 --> 00:01:16.492
respiration,
respiration of organisms where

00:01:16.492 --> 00:01:19.713
there is oxygen,
that oxygen is the terminal

00:01:19.713 --> 00:01:22.453
electron receptor here in that
electron

00:01:22.453 --> 00:01:27.000
transport chain and it's
reduced to water.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.110
So in aerobic environments,
when organisms respire oxygen

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:32.763
it's
reduced to water.

00:01:32.763 --> 00:01:35.577
If there's no oxygen around,
the organisms,

00:01:35.577 --> 00:01:38.355
and in
this case it's always bacteria,

00:01:38.355 --> 00:01:40.872
look for the next
thermodynamically

00:01:40.872 --> 00:01:42.833
favorable electron acceptor.

00:01:42.833 --> 00:01:45.495
And so, whatever is dominant in
that

00:01:45.495 --> 00:01:49.363
environment and is most
thermodynamically favorable,

00:01:49.363 --> 00:01:50.402
they'll
use.

00:01:50.402 --> 00:01:54.327
So, the sulfate reducing
organisms use sulfate and reduce

00:01:54.327 --> 00:01:55.090
to
H2S.

00:01:55.090 --> 00:01:59.373
Denitrifying organisms use
nitrate and reduce it

00:01:59.373 --> 00:02:04.000
to these forms of reduced
nitrate or reduce nitrogen.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.153
And we talked about iron
bacteria Fe plus three,

00:02:07.153 --> 00:02:09.313
and reduce it to
Fe plus two.

00:02:09.313 --> 00:02:11.306
Some can use manganese,
etc.

00:02:11.306 --> 00:02:14.683
Whatever's there,
and it's thermodynamically

00:02:14.683 --> 00:02:16.300
favorable, they'll use.

00:02:16.300 --> 00:02:18.321
OK, so that
clarifies that.

00:02:18.321 --> 00:02:21.711
Some of the people said,
you kept talking about

00:02:21.711 --> 00:02:22.376
symmetry.

00:02:22.376 --> 00:02:24.663
You kept talking about
symmetry.

00:02:24.663 --> 00:02:28.078
I didn't see any
symmetry, and in hindsight I

00:02:28.078 --> 00:02:30.569
can understand why,
because I just

00:02:30.569 --> 00:02:35.000
threw that out and I didn't
really point it out.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.972
So what I was talking about was
as we went through these

00:02:38.972 --> 00:02:42.140
processes, you
see here, these elements,

00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:45.400
sulfate and nitrogen,
nitrate, are being

00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:45.969
reduced.

00:02:45.969 --> 00:02:49.958
There are other processes,
particularly chemosynthesis in

00:02:49.958 --> 00:02:52.357
which
these reduced compounds,

00:02:52.357 --> 00:02:55.360
here's H2S and ammonia are
being oxidized.

00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:59.266
So
that's the symmetry that I was

00:02:59.266 --> 00:03:01.000
talking about.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.556
And if you didn't have that,
if all the organisms were

00:03:04.556 --> 00:03:07.652
reducing things,
the whole system would run

00:03:07.652 --> 00:03:08.002
down.

00:03:08.002 --> 00:03:10.663
You have to have organisms that
are

00:03:10.663 --> 00:03:12.183
also oxidizing things.

00:03:12.183 --> 00:03:15.083
And that's a key component of
all of these,

00:03:15.083 --> 00:03:17.622
or
not all of the biogeochemical

00:03:17.622 --> 00:03:20.331
cycles, but particularly the
cycles

00:03:20.331 --> 00:03:23.506
of nitrogen and sulfur,
which have this redox

00:03:23.506 --> 00:03:24.228
chemistry.

00:03:24.228 --> 00:03:29.109
So that's
the symmetry that I was talking

00:03:29.109 --> 00:03:30.000
about.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:35.537
OK, now so let's talk about how
we think about biogeochemical

00:03:35.537 --> 00:03:36.460
cycles.

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:39.595
Can you see the slide in the
back?

00:03:39.595 --> 00:03:42.160
Try to turn the lights off?

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:45.042
That
was a double question.

00:03:45.042 --> 00:03:48.225
Can you see the slide in the
back?

00:03:48.225 --> 00:03:48.611
Yes?

00:03:48.611 --> 00:03:49.383
OK.

00:03:49.383 --> 00:03:54.908
So this is a generic map of the
components of biogeochemical

00:03:54.908 --> 00:03:55.845
cycles.

00:03:55.845 --> 00:04:01.213
And we can think of the earth
as a giant chemical factory in

00:04:01.213 --> 00:04:04.460
the sense
that has what we call

00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:07.229
compartments,
or reservoirs,

00:04:07.229 --> 00:04:11.038
or pools of
a particular element.

00:04:11.038 --> 00:04:14.713
Or it might be water that we
are

00:04:14.713 --> 00:04:19.056
analyzing, and then there are
fluxes between these pools.

00:04:19.056 --> 00:04:21.272
So here's a
flux, an arrow.

00:04:21.272 --> 00:04:25.569
So typically these are
diagrammed with boxes and arrows

00:04:25.569 --> 00:04:26.971
connecting them.

00:04:26.971 --> 00:04:31.000
And you don't have to use all
of these boxes.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:34.545
It could be we are just looking
at land, atmosphere,

00:04:34.545 --> 00:04:35.240
and ocean.

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:37.117
I
mean, you can construct

00:04:37.117 --> 00:04:39.311
whatever model you want for
these.

00:04:39.311 --> 00:04:42.364
And these
are just some useful conversion

00:04:42.364 --> 00:04:46.458
factors for the amount of things
that we're going to have

00:04:46.458 --> 00:04:48.857
flowing between these
compartments.

00:04:48.857 --> 00:04:50.127
And
here, again,

00:04:50.127 --> 00:04:53.940
this is something we defined
earlier when we were talking

00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:55.281
about productivity.

00:04:55.281 --> 00:04:58.528
The mean residence time of,
say, an element,

00:04:58.528 --> 00:05:02.672
say, carbon in the terrestrial
biomass, is the pool size,

00:05:02.672 --> 00:05:05.163
the
amount of carbon that's there

00:05:05.163 --> 00:05:07.704
divided by the mean flux in or
out

00:05:07.704 --> 00:05:09.031
of the pool,
OK?

00:05:09.031 --> 00:05:12.125
It's exactly the same concept
we

00:05:12.125 --> 00:05:13.625
talked about for carbon.

00:05:13.625 --> 00:05:16.375
And then the fractional
turnover, one over

00:05:16.375 --> 00:05:19.382
the mean residence time is
simply the fraction.

00:05:19.382 --> 00:05:22.544
If we're talking
about carbon again in trees,

00:05:22.544 --> 00:05:24.875
it's the fraction that's
removed

00:05:24.875 --> 00:05:26.192
per unit time.

00:05:26.192 --> 00:05:29.769
OK, so you can see that when we
talk

00:05:29.769 --> 00:05:34.166
about mean residence time of an
element in one of these

00:05:34.166 --> 00:05:37.383
reservoirs,
if the whole system is in a

00:05:37.383 --> 00:05:39.537
steady state,
in other words,

00:05:39.537 --> 00:05:42.951
if the amount
in a reservoir is changing,

00:05:42.951 --> 00:05:46.382
the flux in is going to be the
same as the

00:05:46.382 --> 00:05:47.746
flux out, right?

00:05:47.746 --> 00:05:48.939
You know that.

00:05:48.939 --> 00:05:51.920
Just like a bathtub,
if you have

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:54.613
water flowing in,
water flowing out,

00:05:54.613 --> 00:05:57.459
the level will say the same if
the

00:05:57.459 --> 00:06:03.000
flow rate and is the same as
the flow rate out.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.486
But often in nature,
you don't have that exactly.

00:06:06.486 --> 00:06:08.230
And if you don't,
the

00:06:08.230 --> 00:06:12.702
size of these reservoirs is
either increasing or decreasing.

00:06:12.702 --> 00:06:15.711
So when
you're analyzing these systems,

00:06:15.711 --> 00:06:18.689
your most of the time trying to
get the

00:06:18.689 --> 00:06:22.232
very rough estimate of mean
residence time.

00:06:22.232 --> 00:06:25.758
So if the flow in
and the flow out isn't the

00:06:25.758 --> 00:06:29.151
same, you can either average
them and use that

00:06:29.151 --> 00:06:31.917
as your flux,
or you could define your

00:06:31.917 --> 00:06:36.984
residence time with respect to
the flow in or the flow out.

00:06:36.984 --> 00:06:40.507
So, these are just gross
approximations.

00:06:40.507 --> 00:06:44.199
What we want to understand is
the residence time

00:06:44.199 --> 00:06:46.932
thousands of years,
millions of years,

00:06:46.932 --> 00:06:49.000
days, rough approximation.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.563
And the other thing I want to
say before we go on,

00:06:52.563 --> 00:06:54.759
is that all of
these cycles,

00:06:54.759 --> 00:06:58.600
we're going to talk about them
element by element:

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:00.769
phosphorus, carbon,
whatever.

00:07:00.769 --> 00:07:03.636
But they're all tightly coupled
in

00:07:03.636 --> 00:07:04.441
the system.

00:07:04.441 --> 00:07:07.004
And we'll bring that up again
later.

00:07:07.004 --> 00:07:08.908
Before we go on,
let's

00:07:08.908 --> 00:07:13.540
just look at the solar energy
budget, which is driving this

00:07:13.540 --> 00:07:15.396
whole
system, mostly,

00:07:15.396 --> 00:07:19.452
there is some geothermal
energy, energy from the

00:07:19.452 --> 00:07:24.253
Earth's, the magma that is also
driving biogeochemical cycles.

00:07:24.253 --> 00:07:28.918
But
the solar energy is the primary

00:07:28.918 --> 00:07:30.000
driver.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.601
And if you say that the total
energy from the sun is 100%,

00:07:34.601 --> 00:07:37.295
it's that
energy that is used in

00:07:37.295 --> 00:07:41.139
evaporation, and winds,
and photosynthesis that

00:07:41.139 --> 00:07:44.882
is the important component
driving the cycles.

00:07:44.882 --> 00:07:48.595
And you'll see that
photosynthesis is a tiny

00:07:48.595 --> 00:07:49.301
fraction.

00:07:49.301 --> 00:07:52.283
The energy that plants harvest
is a

00:07:52.283 --> 00:07:56.423
tiny fraction of the total
energy that is driving the

00:07:56.423 --> 00:07:57.855
Earth's system.

00:07:57.855 --> 00:08:02.093
And yet, this photosynthesis,
which is the basis of the

00:08:02.093 --> 00:08:06.455
biosphere, has
an enormous effect on the

00:08:06.455 --> 00:08:09.000
conditions on Earth.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.287
That's an interesting
nonlinearity of the system.

00:08:12.287 --> 00:08:15.506
OK, so let's start
with the geological cycle,

00:08:15.506 --> 00:08:18.452
which is the slowest moving,
people don't

00:08:18.452 --> 00:08:22.380
even think of it as a cycle
because while we are on Earth we

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:24.920
don't see
rocks flying through,

00:08:24.920 --> 00:08:27.906
well, sometimes you see rocks
in a

00:08:27.906 --> 00:08:32.014
landslide or whatever,
but for the most part you don't

00:08:32.014 --> 00:08:34.308
think
of rocks as cycling.

00:08:34.308 --> 00:08:35.312
But they do.

00:08:35.312 --> 00:08:39.171
And if they didn't,
the system would run down much

00:08:39.171 --> 00:08:40.383
faster than it is.

00:08:40.383 --> 00:08:43.183
And we've all
heard about plate tectonics,

00:08:43.183 --> 00:08:45.768
that the surface of the Earth
is made up

00:08:45.768 --> 00:08:48.378
of these plates that are slowly
shifting.

00:08:48.378 --> 00:08:51.185
And when they shift you
have earthquakes,

00:08:51.185 --> 00:08:53.274
like we've had recently a lot
of.

00:08:53.274 --> 00:08:56.184
And also, you
have volcanic eruptions that

00:08:56.184 --> 00:08:58.692
bring material from the inside
of the

00:08:58.692 --> 00:09:03.000
Earth up to the surface and it
overflows.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.374
And that's part of this
geological cycle.

00:09:06.374 --> 00:09:09.350
So, here's a really
oversimplified,

00:09:09.350 --> 00:09:13.460
when the geology professor in
our department saw that

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:17.704
ever showing this he had a
heart attack by how simplified

00:09:17.704 --> 00:09:18.159
it is.

00:09:18.159 --> 00:09:20.869
But
it's just so you get the idea.

00:09:20.869 --> 00:09:23.919
When he started editing it,
there are so

00:09:23.919 --> 00:09:27.139
many arrows you can never cope
with that.

00:09:27.139 --> 00:09:29.150
But just get the idea.

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:33.473
There's geothermal energy
coming in from the inner core of

00:09:33.473 --> 00:09:36.220
the Earth
where you have magma.

00:09:36.220 --> 00:09:39.544
Think volcanic eruption,
lava, which

00:09:39.544 --> 00:09:41.871
ultimately becomes surface
rocks.

00:09:41.871 --> 00:09:44.634
And they're eroded by
weathering by

00:09:44.634 --> 00:09:48.343
rain, and then elements from
that go into the soils.

00:09:48.343 --> 00:09:51.683
Soils eventually
become sedimentary rocks.

00:09:51.683 --> 00:09:54.816
We're talking over really,
really long

00:09:54.816 --> 00:09:58.550
time periods,
which become metamorphic rocks.

00:09:58.550 --> 00:10:01.029
Some of those
are uplifted,

00:10:01.029 --> 00:10:05.000
and some of them are melted and
become magma.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.652
But it is a cycle,
a very, very slow cycle.

00:10:08.652 --> 00:10:13.399
In fact, somewhere I read
70%, you do not need to know

00:10:13.399 --> 00:10:13.828
this.

00:10:13.828 --> 00:10:16.057
This is not geology class.

00:10:16.057 --> 00:10:18.904
But just
so you have an idea,

00:10:18.904 --> 00:10:23.000
75% of the rocks now on the
surface of the

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.595
earth have been uplifted.

00:10:25.595 --> 00:10:29.332
So it's almost as if the Earth
is,

00:10:29.332 --> 00:10:33.237
on average, maybe halfway
through a cycle.

00:10:33.237 --> 00:10:35.999
So, this erosion here,
and

00:10:35.999 --> 00:10:42.664
weathering, as we talked about
last time is critical for making

00:10:42.664 --> 00:10:46.664
nutrients available to the
biosphere.

00:10:46.664 --> 00:10:51.755
And the force of this
weathering is incredibly

00:10:51.755 --> 00:10:52.664
powerful.

00:10:52.664 --> 00:10:58.405
One number that I found in one
textbook that I never knew

00:10:58.405 --> 00:11:02.664
before is that Niagara Falls is
eroding at 3

00:11:02.664 --> 00:11:04.437
feet per year.

00:11:04.437 --> 00:11:09.250
The cusp of the falls from the
water

00:11:09.250 --> 00:11:12.213
is moving back 3 feet per year.

00:11:12.213 --> 00:11:13.360
That's fast.

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:18.277
Another little factoid
when I gave this lecture one

00:11:18.277 --> 00:11:22.250
year, students asked what is
going to burn

00:11:22.250 --> 00:11:27.049
out first on the Earth,
the sun or the geothermal

00:11:27.049 --> 00:11:27.750
energy?

00:11:27.750 --> 00:11:30.539
And of
course I had no idea.

00:11:30.539 --> 00:11:32.755
This will be over someday.

00:11:32.755 --> 00:11:36.815
The Earth is going
to be history because without

00:11:36.815 --> 00:11:39.634
the sun and without the
geothermal

00:11:39.634 --> 00:11:42.072
energy there's no source of
energy.

00:11:42.072 --> 00:11:44.725
So I went to my colleagues in
this

00:11:44.725 --> 00:11:48.487
department, Earth Atmosphere
and Planetary Sciences,

00:11:48.487 --> 00:11:51.899
and said, which
is going to burn out first?

00:11:51.899 --> 00:11:54.908
And they said,
roughly the same time.

00:11:54.908 --> 00:12:00.000
And we have about 2 billion
years, so not to worry yet.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.346
But it is, we are only here for
a period of time.

00:12:03.346 --> 00:12:05.517
So, that's the
geologic cycle.

00:12:05.517 --> 00:12:09.063
Now, let's move onto the water
cycle, and then we're

00:12:09.063 --> 00:12:12.397
going to go through the element
cycles of nitrogen,

00:12:12.397 --> 00:12:14.100
phosphorus, and
carbon.

00:12:14.100 --> 00:12:18.130
But the water cycle is
obviously important in carrying

00:12:18.130 --> 00:12:20.398
those elements through their
cycles.

00:12:20.398 --> 00:12:22.664
And the cycle is actually
fairly

00:12:22.664 --> 00:12:23.816
well understood.

00:12:23.816 --> 00:12:27.198
I say fairly because not all of
these things,

00:12:27.198 --> 00:12:31.731
when you're talking about
global averages of things it's

00:12:31.731 --> 00:12:33.253
very difficult.

00:12:33.253 --> 00:12:39.076
But the weather service is very
interested in the global water

00:12:39.076 --> 00:12:39.571
cycle.

00:12:39.571 --> 00:12:42.737
So there's been a lot of
study done.

00:12:42.737 --> 00:12:47.000
So in terms of reservoirs,
these numbers in black

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.120
are the amounts of water in a
reservoir.

00:12:50.120 --> 00:12:54.120
And the numbers in blue
are the number of fluxes

00:12:54.120 --> 00:12:57.399
annually of the amounts of water
moving

00:12:57.399 --> 00:12:59.623
from one to another.

00:12:59.623 --> 00:13:04.256
So, there is a lot of water in
groundwater.

00:13:04.256 --> 00:13:09.543
There's a lot of water in ice,
and there's a lot of water

00:13:09.543 --> 00:13:10.935
in the oceans.

00:13:10.935 --> 00:13:15.907
And there's very little water
in the atmosphere.

00:13:15.907 --> 00:13:18.416
These are the annual fluxes.

00:13:18.416 --> 00:13:22.270
So you can see,
if I animated this right,

00:13:22.270 --> 00:13:27.086
so 111, these are in terms of
square kilometers of water,

00:13:27.086 --> 00:13:29.261
that's a lot of
water.

00:13:29.261 --> 00:13:32.391
So, 111 minus 71 gives you 40.

00:13:32.391 --> 00:13:35.000
So that's the rainfall.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.104
This is the evapotranspiration,
and the net result is 40,000

00:13:39.104 --> 00:13:41.422
that is
flowing into the oceans.

00:13:41.422 --> 00:13:44.599
And in the oceans,
here's the evaporation and

00:13:44.599 --> 00:13:48.438
here's the rainfall going in
with just a net of 40 that's

00:13:48.438 --> 00:13:51.118
transported
from the oceans to land.

00:13:51.118 --> 00:13:54.198
So you have 40,000 going into
the oceans,

00:13:54.198 --> 00:13:57.879
and 40,000 coming back,
